= //**Act II, Scene 13.**//



= {{**Department of Unreality, interior-exterior-//betweenerior//. — dusk, complacency.**}}



@@ @@

@@ @@

@@ @@

@@ @@



//**ALEX THORLEY** continues idly tapping away at the keyboard, their fingers brushing against cheap plastic keys the colour of… beige?//[[footnote]]Beige? Thorley clearly meant manilla. How could that hideous colour have ever been considered the vogue for interior decorating?[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@I’m just going through the motions. That’s all.



//**ALEX THORLEY** continues tapping away at the keyboard. The cheap plastic keys have worn away. There are no letters; only faint impressions. An inordinate amount of time passes. There are no burgers, no bagels, not even sushi — just **ALEX THORLEY** and a keyboard.//[[footnote]]There are other things aside from Thorley and a keyboard in this place, but they’re relatively unimportant in the here and now. You’ll see.[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@I could have this finished tonight if I tried.



//**ALEX THORLEY** continues tapping away at the keyboard. Each fingerstroke compresses and decompresses the spring. Letters shuffle across the piece of paper before them.//[[footnote]]Thorley wouldn't have been finished tonight. If they had been able to be finished by tonight, they would have been finished by tonight.[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@Or the night before.



//**ALEX THORLEY** sighs as they continue typing, each stroke of their fingers leaving a smudge upon the keys. Even if they were to delete everything upon the page, the smudges would remain and that's something.//[[footnote]]Thorley wouldn't have been finished the night before. Again, if they had been able to be finished the night before, they would have been finished the night before.[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@I’m hungry.



//**ALEX THORLEY** stands up from the desk and peels their fingers away from the keyboard. In the absence of **ALEX THORLEY**, all that remains upon the keyboard is a sweaty patina of fingerprints.//



@@ @@

@@ @@

----

@@ @@

@@ @@



= //**Act II, Scene 512.**//



= {{**Department of Unreality, interior-exterior-//betweenerior//. — night, wisenheimer.**}}



@@ @@

@@ @@

@@ @@

@@ @@



//**ALEX THORLEY** continues idly tapping away at the keyboard, their fingers brushing against cheap, yellowed plastic keys.//[[footnote]]Better, though how that colour ever became associated with interior design is a mystery to us all.[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@“Nothing upon nothing upon nothing.”



//**ALEX THORLEY** looks at the piece of paper before them. There's more letters upon it now than ever before. Not all of them are good; some of them might even be described as bad — worse, some of them might be described as pointless. If **ALEX THORLEY** squints, they might be described as words.//[[footnote]]Thorley, of course, knows better than to listen to the solipsistic delusions of a dreaming unconsciousness. Their design is but a pale shade of another.[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@I'm not asleep, am I?



//**ALEX THORLEY** turns around and looks over their shoulder. A sea of endless office cubicles surrounds their own cubicle; an island all to their lonesome. Sounds of endless, repeated keystrokes fill their ears, but **ALEX THORLEY** is all alone.//[[footnote]]Thorley isn't alone – but then they don't know this – do they?[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@I'm hungry again.



//**ALEX THORLEY** reaches into the desk's compartment. It is cold, dark, and damp. Their hand brushes against something, but comes away covered in dust. There is no point to exploring the rest of the desk. **ALEX THORLEY** closes the compartment and sighs dejectedly.//[[footnote]]Their work continues.[[/footnote]]



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@Why am I always hungry?



//**ALEX THORLEY** receives nothing but silence in answer. To feel alone is natural, and natural things are comforting. But to know that you are alone – truly alone – is a discomforting, terrifying sensation. In this moment, **ALEX THORLEY** knows they are alone. They pick up the keyboard, balancing it between their two hands, before bringing it down across their knee. It snaps.//



@@ @@

@@ @@

----

@@ @@

@@ @@



= //**Act II, Scene 1276.**//



= {{**Department of Unreality, interior-exterior-//betweenerior//. — morning, satisfactory.**}}



@@ @@

@@ @@

@@ @@

@@ @@



//**ALEX THORLEY** is no longer tapping away at the keyboard. Instead their fingers idly dance upon the surface of the desk. They flick through the manilla folders in their desk's compartment. They are organised alphabetically and none of them are marked by red lines. Instinct or habit, **ALEX THORLEY** is unsure, but what they are sure of is that **ALEX THORLEY** had nothing left to do.//



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@And—



//**ALEX THORLEY** sighs in relief. They stand up from their desk and pace around the office cubicle. The first lap takes thirteen seconds. By the twenty-fifth lap, it only takes them four. They smile and lie down on the floor. Exhaustion floods through their mind. There is nothing. Their consciousness focuses upon the darkness. **ALEX THORLEY** has nothing left to do.//



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@—I'm done.



//**ALEX THORLEY** stands up and looks around their office for a moment. A halogen light buzzes somewhere in the distance. The sound of rapid keystrokes slowly fades into the tones of piano keys being struck. A scent of manilla folders wafts through the room. **ALEX THORLEY** still had nothing left to do.//



//**ALEX THORLEY**//

@@    @@I don't feel hungry today.



//**ALEX THORLEY** exits stage left.//

